explanation: OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro) - must be inspected because it is a macro expanded inside OS_BinSemGetIdByName; macros operate by textual substitution and can modify the parameter variables (e.g. assign to sem_id or sem_name) in the caller, which would violate the MISRA rule if present. OS_ObjectIdFindByName (function or macro) - the call passes sem_name and sem_id; if this symbol is a macro it could modify the caller's parameter variables via textual expansion. Even if a function, its implementation must be reviewed to confirm it does not rely on callers' parameter identifiers via macros or otherwise cause modification. OS_ObjectIdGetByName and OS_ObjectIdRelease (callees of OS_ObjectIdFindByName) - include to follow the transitive implementation of OS_ObjectIdFindByName in case pointer reassignment or unusual macro behavior occurs deeper in the call chain. LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE (constant/macro) - include to confirm whether it is a macro that could expand to code that affects the call site (if it were a complex macro) or otherwise changes how OS_ObjectIdFindByName is invoked. OS_printf - appears in the target's callee list (likely via macro expansions such as OS_CHECK_POINTER); include to check whether any logging macros expand in a way that assign to parameter variables. UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr - these unit-test stub symbols appear in the static call graph as callees (likely from macro/test scaffolding expansions). Include them to inspect any test-framework macros/handlers that may be expanded inline and that could alter the parameter variables in the caller. Together these symbols cover all macro expansions and transitive callees that could cause modification of the pointer parameters (the pointer variables sem_id and sem_name) in OS_BinSemGetIdByName; verifying their definitions will determine compliance with the MISRA rule.
